No, you cannot modify the GUI from another thread, use the signals.

**TL;DR;**

I share a golden rule in Qt: You cannot and should not modify the GUI from another thread. For more information read: [GUI Thread and Worker Thread][1].

Considering the above, the natural way to interact between elements that live in different threads in Qt is to use the signals since they are [thread-safe][2] as I show below:

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;class Main(QMainWindow):
    &lt;b&gt;customSignal = pyqtSignal()&lt;/b&gt;

    def __init__(self):
        # ...
        
        self.show()
        &lt;b&gt;self.customSignal.connect(self.dialog.exec_)&lt;/b&gt;

    def show_dialog(self):
        Thread(target=self.execute).start()

    def execute(self):
        sleep(2)
        # keep moving mainwindow untill dialog have shown
        &lt;b&gt;self.customSignal.emit()&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;


  [1]: https://doc.qt.io/qt-5/thread-basics.html#gui-thread-and-worker-thread
  [2]: https://doc.qt.io/qt-5/threads-reentrancy.html

You can use [Dynamic Arguments][1], e.g. (being `event_name` the constant):

    &lt;MyComponent @[event_name]=&quot;myHandler&quot; /&gt;

but with some caveats:

- There are [several constraints][2] to what you can use inside the `[]`;
- For the `event_name` constant to be used in the template, it **must be accessible to the template**, which means it should be a `data` property, a computed, or similar. It does not suffice to merely be declared in the script, outside of the vue component.
- Attributes will be parsed as lowercase, so your constant must be `event_name`, not `EVENT_NAME` or `Event_Name` (you can even use those, but they will be treated as `event_name`; see how I declare the `data` below).

Working demo:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const EVENT_NAME = &#39;some-event&#39;;

    Vue.component(`my-component`, {
      template: `
        &lt;button @click=&quot;myCompInternalHandler&quot;&gt;click me to emit an event whose name is the value of event_name&lt;/button&gt;
      `,
      methods: {
        myCompInternalHandler() {
          this.$emit(EVENT_NAME, {someData: 112233});
        }
      }
    });

    new Vue({
      el: &#39;#app&#39;,
      data: {
        message: &#39;Hello Vue.js!&#39;,
        event_name: EVENT_NAME // key has to be lowercase, because it is used in the template as dynamic attr
      },
      methods: {
        myHandler(e) {
          console.log(&#39;received at parent:&#39;, e);
        }
      }
    })

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;script src=&quot;https://unpkg.com/vue&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;

    &lt;div id=&quot;app&quot;&gt;
      &lt;my-component @[event_name]=&quot;myHandler&quot; /&gt;
      &lt;p&gt;{{ message }}&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


  [1]: https://vuejs.org/v2/guide/syntax.html#Dynamic-Arguments
  [2]: https://vuejs.org/v2/guide/syntax.html#Dynamic-Argument-Expression-Constraints

