`||` will exit as soon as possible so if `deleteUsers` returns `true` it will not execute `deleteAccounts` or `deleteMoney`.

But this still looks strange because nothing suggests that `deleteXXX` functions return `true` in case something wents wrong. You should rather reverse this logic and use `&amp;&amp;` instead of `||`

This is just a *warning* and alerting you that you might be doing the wrong thing, obviously the actions will execute with in the context and it wont be disposed.

If this is a *resharper* warning you can disable this with a a comment 

